{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501189"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:25:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:25:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1730"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1730"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.02,0.76,0.14,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114840"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1730"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96840"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4208"},{"type":"tags","id":"4734"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"4924"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3982"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38842"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114840"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of crampy lower abdominal pain and nausea. Her last menstrual period was four weeks ago and she takes the oral contraceptive pill. She has no significant medical history and does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. She has tenderness in the right iliac fossa with guarding. Endocervical swabs are taken and a beta-human chorionic gonadotropin (\u03b2-hCG) test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step to investigate the suspected diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["White cell count","C-reactive protein","Ultrasound of the lower abdomen and pelvis","Computed tomography scan of the abdomen and pelvis","Diagnostic laparoscopy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with right iliac fossa pain and clinical features suggestive of appendicitis. However, in women of reproductive age, several gynaecological conditions must be considered in the differential diagnosis. These include ovarian torsion, ruptured ovarian cyst, pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), endometriosis, and ectopic pregnancy. Although the \u03b2-hCG is negative, ruling out pregnancy, and she is on oral contraceptive pills which reduce the risk of ovarian cysts, these other gynaecological conditions remain possible. PID is particularly important to consider given the endocervical swabs that were taken, suggesting this was part of the clinical suspicion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the lower abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation. It is non-invasive, does not involve radiation exposure, and can effectively evaluate both the appendix and gynaecological structures. Ultrasound has good sensitivity and specificity for appendicitis and can identify alternative diagnoses such as ovarian pathology or PID. In women of reproductive age, ultrasound should be the first-line imaging modality to avoid unnecessary radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhite cell count\u003C/strong\u003E would likely be elevated in appendicitis but is non-specific and can be raised in many inflammatory or infectious conditions, including gynaecological pathologies. While it may support the diagnosis, it would not be diagnostic on its own and would not help differentiate between appendicitis and gynaecological causes of pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC-reactive protein\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute phase reactant that rises in response to inflammation. Like white cell count, it lacks specificity for appendicitis and would not help distinguish between appendicitis and gynaecological causes of right iliac fossa pain. It is useful as a supporting test but not as the next most appropriate investigation in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography scan of the abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E has excellent sensitivity and specificity for appendicitis, higher than ultrasound. However, it involves significant radiation exposure, which should be avoided in women of reproductive age if possible. CT would be appropriate if ultrasound findings were inconclusive and there remained high clinical suspicion for appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic laparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is both diagnostic and potentially therapeutic but is invasive and carries surgical risks. It would be considered if imaging studies were inconclusive and there remained high clinical suspicion for a surgical condition requiring intervention. It is not appropriate as the next investigation before non-invasive imaging has been performed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultrasound is the preferred initial imaging modality for suspected appendicitis in women of reproductive age to avoid radiation exposure.","Appendicitis is the most common non-obstetric surgical emergency during pregnancy.","Differential diagnosis for right iliac fossa pain in women includes gynaecological conditions such as ovarian torsion, ruptured ovarian cyst, and pelvic inflammatory disease."],"references":["Sayem M, Akter R, Karim, M, et al. Diagnostic dilemma of right iliac fossa pain in females: a prospective study of 100 cases. International Surgery Journal. 2024;11(6):947\u2013952. Available at: https://www.ijsurgery.com/index.php/isj/article/view/10412","Le L, Walizai T, Silverstone L, et al. Acute appendicitis. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 01 Jan 2025). Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/acute-appendicitis-2#nav_radiographic-features"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96840"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1730"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96840"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17:55:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T17:55:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1730"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114840"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"